[3] Australia (NSW)
Date: Wed 25 Jul 2012
source: Campbelltown-Macarthur Advertiser [edited]
http://www.macarthuradvertiser.com.au/news/local/news/general/moves-to-contain-measles-outbreak/2635057.aspx

Moves to contain measles outbreak
------------------------------
Measles is spreading through the Campbelltown area after first appearing in Eagle Vale last month. South Western Sydney Local Health District director of public health Stephen Conaty said there had been at least 22 local cases of measles since the beginning of June and the disease had now spread to suburbs around Eagle Vale. "Measles is very infectious and so it's possible that we could see a huge outbreak," Dr Conaty told the Advertiser. He said the disease was not common in Australia and could have been brought to Sydney by someone who had travelled overseas. "All the cases of measles that we see are really imported from elsewhere, and we can see some local transmission after that," Dr Conaty said.

Those born since 1966 who have not had two doses of the MMR vaccine, or a previous measles infection, are considered most susceptible. The majority of people who have been diagnosed locally have been teenagers and young children that had not been immunised, including five infants. "What's really important is that people are aware of the symptoms -- a cough, running nose and then a rash that follows [a few days later]," Dr Conaty said. He said people should see a doctor if they had these symptoms, but should call and notify the doctor's surgery before arriving to avoid spreading the virus. For young children, the MMR vaccination is recommended at 12 months and again at four years of age.

